      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What are macros and why do they matter?</summary>
        <p>Macros are the three macronutrients that provide calories: protein (4 cal/g), carbohydrates (4 cal/g), and fat (9 cal/g). They matter because the ratio in which you consume them affects body composition, energy, performance, and hunger. Two people eating the same total calories but different macro ratios can have different results. Use our <a href="/macro/">macro calculator</a> to find your ideal split.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I calculate my ideal macro split?</summary>
        <p>Start with your daily calorie target, then set protein first at 0.7 to 1 gram per pound of body weight, fat at 0.3 to 0.4 grams per pound (minimum 20 percent of calories), and fill the rest with carbohydrates. For example, a 160-pound person eating 2,000 calories might aim for 160g protein, 55g fat, and 215g carbs, roughly a 32/25/43 percent split.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do I need to hit my macros exactly every day?</summary>
        <p>No. Being within 5 to 10 grams of each target is sufficient. Consistency over weeks matters far more than daily perfection. Prioritize hitting your protein target since it has the greatest impact on body composition and satiety. Fat and carbs can fluctuate more as long as your weekly averages and total calories stay on track.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is flexible dieting or IIFYM?</summary>
        <p>Flexible dieting (If It Fits Your Macros) focuses on meeting daily macro targets rather than following rigid meal plans. You have freedom to choose which foods make up your targets, with the recommendation that 80 percent come from whole, nutrient-dense foods. Research shows flexible approaches produce better long-term adherence and psychological outcomes than rigid dieting.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the most common macro counting mistakes?</summary>
        <p>The biggest mistakes are not weighing food (leading to inaccurate estimates), forgetting to track cooking oils and condiments, setting protein too low, being overly rigid (causing burnout), and copying someone else's macros instead of calculating your own. Using a food scale and tracking app eliminates most of these issues.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

